'''Michael Richard Parisi''' (born [[April 18]], [[1983]] in [[Huntington, New York]]) is a [[Minor league baseball]] [[right-handed]] [[starting pitcher]] for the [[Memphis Redbirds]] (AAA) in the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] organization.

He was drafted in the 9th round of the 2004 MLB draft by the St. Louis Cardinals. He also was invited to [[spring training]] in {{by|2007}} and {{by|2008}}. Parisi went to and graduated [[Manhattan College]] in 2006 and was a pitcher for the Manhattan College Jaspers. On [[November 20]], [[2007]], Parisi was added to the Cardinals 40-man roster in order to keep him from being lost in the [[Rule 5 draft]].

On [[May 4]], 2008, Parisi was called up to the big-league club.<ref>[http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080504&content_id=2642436&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl Parisi called up]</ref>  Parisi made his MLB debut on [[May 5]], 2008 at [[Coors Field]]. He pitched a scoreless inning of relief and his first career [[strikeout]] was against [[Matt Herges]].

On [[November 20]], 2008, the Cardinals [[designated for assignment|outrighted]] him to its AAA affiliate ([[Memphis Redbirds]]), reducing their 40-man roster to 36.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20081121&content_id=3687693&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=Cardinals outright Parisi to Minors |publisher=MLB.com |date=2008-11-21 |accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref>

Parisi is only the second Major League Baseball player to hail from Sachem High School in Lake Ronkonkoma, New York on Long Island. 


